- ## Monitoring
#Monitoring #Scenarios #SystemsofSystems #Monitoring #Challenges #Requirements #Monitoring 
A. Scenario 1 – Cross-system runtime monitoring Systems in industrial SoS are developed independently by different teams or even companies. Systems are first tested in isolation, e.g., using test suites and tools simulating missing machinery (e.g., sensor signals) or expected input data from other systems. During commissioning [13], software systems are integrated with hardware for the first time. During both simulation and commissioning, engineers need support to monitor behavior across systems in the SoS.

Scenario 2 – Analysis via capture & replay Although runtime monitoring aims at detecting and re- porting violations immediately, there are cases where live monitoring is not possible or not even desired. - ## ReMinds
#ReMinds #Frameworks #Requirements #Monitoring 
tool suite supports developing probes [14] to instrument heterogeneous systems in an SoS. It facilitates the definition of event models to aggregate events and event data provided by the probes,

- ## ReMinds
#ReMinds #Frameworks #Requirements #Monitoring 
probes for Java-based systems, for systems developed in C++, as well as for Oracle and MSSQL databases.

- ## ReMinds
#ReMinds #Frameworks #Requirements #Monitoring 
The separation of low-level event handling and high-level constraint management allows to check cross- cutting and global constraints, which require data aggregated from various systems. Examples include behavioral constraints such as event sequences, conditions on event occurrence, as well as invariant checks performed on the data associated with monitored events.

- ## Tools
